@rdblue I am not familiar with Avro, some of my considerations (may not right, please point out) :
1. Druid support limited dimensions with String and list of String, so nested structure is not needed. This make the implementation simple enough;
2. Avro need a Schema File to generate object. If dynamic schema is supported, there is still a problem that data types may mismatch with parquet files. From this perspective, a strict matched schema file must be provided. And the last, with an Avro object, another kind of converters are also needed to traverse class fields to do transformation. 

Actually I refer a lot to parquet-pig, I just want to keep it simple.

@du00cs, parquet-avro will convert the schema of the Parquet file to an Avro schema for you. What you end up with is a GenericRecord object with the data for a row, without writing several converter classes.

For nested data, parquet-avro support doesn't impose a nested structure, but it can handle nesting if that's what the file contains. Parquet supports nesting just like Avro so it's better to have an object model that can deal with it, even if you ignore the map and array columns.

I think using a pre-built object model will be the simplest way forward. And if you built on parquet-avro, you'd be 95% of the way to support for Avro files.

@b-slim  LookupCoordinatorManager should be running on the coordinator. All it does is make sure the entry in the auditable config metadata is kept reasonable, and the config changes are propagated around to the nodes.

The LookupCoordinatorManager doesn't actually do anything with lookups, it just propagates configs.

The LookupReferencesManager runs on the nodes, and takes updates via io.druid.query.extraction.LookupListeningResource in LookupExtractionModule

currently RTR uses SingleThreadExecutor that causes overlord to be blocked waiting for a worker to acknowledge the task assigned. We can use a multiple thread executor instead and keep a set of workers (who have not acknowledged at least one task) and not consider them in the pool of workers to which a new task can be assigned.
then if one worker is down, only one task will fail but overlord will continue to make progress with other tasks.

